# Invert `if`s — flatten nesting with guard clauses

## Rule

Prefer **guard clauses** and **early exits** over nesting the main logic inside positive branches. When a branch only handles an exceptional, empty, or short path (**`return`**, **`throw`**, **`continue`**, **`break`**), structure it so that path is handled first and the remainder of the block stays **out** of extra braces.

Treat “invert `if`” as: **negate or reorder** the condition so the early-exit stays at the top, and the default / happy path flows straight down at **minimal indentation**.

## Preferred

```csharp
public void Handle(Request request)
{
    if (request is null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(request));
    if (!request.IsValid) return;

    Process(request);
}
```

```csharp
// Prefer early continue over wrapping the loop body
foreach (Item item in items)
{
    if (item is null || item.IsArchived) continue;

    Process(item);
}
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid — burying the happy path one level deeper
public void Handle(Request request)
{
    if (request is not null)
    {
        if (request.IsValid)
        {
            Process(request);
        }
    }
}
```

```csharp
// Avoid — redundant else after a terminating branch (use fall-through)
if (x)
{
    return;
}
else
{
    DoWork();
}
```

## When *not* to force inversion

Keep symmetric **`if` / `else if` / `else`** (or a **`switch`** / **`switch` expression**) when **every** branch is a **peer** computation at the same level (mapping, routing, parsers) and inverting would harm readability — in those cases **`CSharp-Terse-03-SwitchExpressions.mdc`** still applies where it fits.

## Companion rules

- **`CSharp-Terse-12-EarlyReturnNoTrailingElse.mdc`** — no trailing `else` after a guarded return/throw/break/continue.
- **`CSharp-Terse-01-GuardClausesSameLine.mdc`** — same-line guards when the line stays readable.
- **`CSharp-Whitespace-MaxSingleBlankLine.mdc`** — after refactoring, keep **at most one** blank line between logical lines; still respect **one blank line before** an `if` / `foreach` when that is the first statement after another statement in the same block (team norm).
